|Ship armour= |Ship notes= }} |} '''''Minerve''''' was a [[France|French]] [[submarine]], one of nine of the {{sclass-|Daphné|submarine|4}}. The relatively small submarine was an experimental missile-carrying submarine with a diesel engine. She had a maximum speed of {{convert|15|kn}}.
==Service history== ''Minerve'' was laid down in May 1958 at the ''Chantiers Dubigeon'' shipyard in [[Nantes]], and launched on 31 May 1961. After a [[shakedown cruise]] to [[Londonderry Port]], [[Bergen]], and [[Gothenburg]] in November 1962, the submarine sailed from [[Cherbourg]] to [[Toulon]], arriving on 22 December 1962. She was commissioned into the 1st Submarine Squadron on 10 June 1964. ''Minerve'' operated solely in the Mediterranean, and was refitted at Missiessy Quay, Toulon, in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.netmarine.net/bat/smarins/minerve/index.htm |title=Sous-marin ''Minerve'' |first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |work=netmarine.net |year=2012 |accessdate=6 February 2013|language=fr}}</ref>
===Loss=== On 27 January 1968 at 07:55 hrs, ''Minerve'' was travelling just under the surface using her [[submarine snorkel|snorkel]], roughly {{Convert|25|nmi|km}} from her base in [[Toulon]], when she advised an accompanying [[Breguet Atlantic]] aircraft that she would be at her berth in about an hour; 52 crew, including six officers, were on board. She was never heard from again. She was lost in waters between {{Convert|1000|m|ft}} and {{Convert|2000|m|ft}} deep.<ref name="disparitionssousmarins">{{cite web |url= http://s.m.minerve.free.fr/circons.html |title=La tragédie de la Minerve |accessdate=22 September 2013|language=fr}}</ref>
[[Commander]] Philipe Bouillot later said that ''Minerve''{{'}}s new captain [[Lieutenant]] André Fauve had spent 7,000 hours submerged over four years on submarines of the same class and never had a problem. The only factor known that could have caused her to sink was the weather, which was extremely bad at the time of her loss.<ref name="disparitionssousmarins"/>
The French Navy promptly launched a search for the missing submarine mobilizing numerous ships, including the aircraft carrier {{Ship|French aircraft carrier|Clemenceau|R98|2}} and the submersible ''[[SP-350 Denise]]'' under the supervision of [[Jacques Cousteau]], but found nothing, and the operation was called off on 2 February. However, the search for ''Minerve'', under the name ''Operation Reminer'' continued into 1969 and utilized the submersible ''[[Archimède]]'' and the US survey ship {{USNS|Mizar|T-AGOR-11|6}}. To this day no trace of the vessel has been found.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.netmarine.net/bat/smarins/minerve/histoire.htm |title=Historique du sous-marin ''Minerve'' |first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |work=netmarine.net |year=2012 |accessdate=6 February 2013|language=fr}}</ref>
''Minerve'' was lost at about the same time as the {{Ship|INS|Dakar}} (a few days apart), over {{Convert|1450|mi|km}} away. Two more submarines were lost to unknown causes in the same year, the [[Soviet submarine K-129 (1960)|Soviet submarine ''K-129'']] and the US submarine {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|6}}.
